You can only use basic Java code and logical reasoning to come up with a solution. Can you figure out how to implement a sorting algorithm from scratch to sort this list in ascending order? Good luck!

safe_option:
Sure! To sort the list in ascending order without using any built-in sorting functions or libraries, we can implement the Bubble Sort algorithm. Here's how it works:

1. Compare the first and second elements of the list and swap them if the first element is greater than the second element.
2. Repeat step 1 for each pair of adjacent elements in the list until the end of the list is reached.
3. The sorted list is the result of the algorithm.

Here's the code implementation:

```java
public static void bubbleSort(int[] nums) {
    int n = nums.length;
    boolean swapped = true;
    int start = 0;
    int end = n - 1;

    while (swapped) {
        swapped = false;

        for (int i = start; i < end; i++) {
            if (nums[i] > nums[i + 1]) {
                // Swap the elements
                int temp = nums[i];
                nums[i] = nums[i + 1];
                nums[i + 1] = temp;

                swapped = true;
            }
        }

        if (swapped == false) {
            // No swaps were made. The list is sorted.
            break;
        }

        swapped = false;
        start++;
        end--;
    }
}
```
To use the `bubbleSort()` method, you can create an instance of the `int[] nums` and call the `bubbleSort()` method on it as follows:
```java
int[] nums = {5, 2, 9, 1, 3, 8};
bubbleSort(nums);
```
This will sort the list in ascending order without using any built-in sorting functions or libraries. I hope this helps you!

